Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest and have the @lemon{1/2}(zested). Trim the @green beans{80}(trimmed) and chop into thirds.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large saucepan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the onion and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Cook the onion until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}, stir every minute or so. Once soft, stir in half the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the @orzo{180}. Pour in the @water{450} and the @vegetable stock powder{1}.

Stir the mixture together and bring to a simmer. Cook until the orzo is tender, ~{12-14%minutes}. Stir regularly to stop it sticking to the bottom of the pan.

Meanwhile heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the beans and cook until slightly charred, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the @king prawns{150} and remaining garlic along with a splash of water. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when opaque all the way through. Remove the pan from the heat.

Once the orzo is cooked, remove from the heat. TIP: If the orzo is not quite cooked but the stock has been absorbed, just add a splash more water and keep cooking until it's tender. Add the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40}, @harissa paste{50}, prawns, beans and a pinch of lemon zest. Stir together gently until well combined.

Add a squeeze of lemon to the orzo, taste and add more salt, pepper and lemon juice if you feel it needs it. Spoon into #bowls{} and finish with a sprinkle of remaining lemon zest. Enjoy!

> Looking for a simple showstopper you can rustle together in just twenty-five minutes? Look no further. The African blend of Harissa is no ordinary spice mix, which is exactly why it's the hero ingredient in tonight's recipe. A crunchy mix of green beans and juicy prawns works beautifully with orzo.